    p1.write(0);
    p4.write(0);	  
    wait(0.5);	

    p1.write(1);
    p4.write(1);

    wait(0.5);			
    }
```

Though my debugger is not showing any toggling for P0_13, it cannot be manipulated over debugger nor read correctly (always 0)

![toggle](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/25270775/33482936-a1cba79e-d69b-11e7-8308-9eae9881226f.PNG)

Nor can the value be read correctly for P0_13 in code:   `p1.read()`.  *Is this behaviour intentional? Or are there any other registers that need to be configured to be able to read the value correctly?*

I am asking because programs that use operator overloading (which use gpio read method) dont work correctly for ISP able pins:

```
 while (true) {						
        p1 = !p1;      // ISP able;   does not work beacuse the value cannot be read correctly
	p4 = !p4;     // ISP unable, works fine 
